    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What is the most valuable card in the Destined Rivals card list?</summary>
        <p>The most sought-after and valuable cards typically include the Secret Rare alternate arts of the cover monster and high-utility staple spell cards that see play across multiple competitive decks. Their scarcity and high demand drive up their secondary market price significantly.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How many cards are included in a standard Destined Rivals booster box?</summary>
        <p>A standard core booster box contains 24 packs. With 9 cards per pack, you receive 216 total cards per box. The set itself features a specific pool of unique cards divided into Commons, Super Rares, Ultra Rares, and Secret Rares, meaning you will not get a complete set from a single box.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Are there any reprinted staples in the Destined Rivals set?</summary>
        <p>Yes, sets like Destined Rivals frequently include critical reprints of hand traps and board breakers that were previously difficult to acquire or overly expensive. This makes it an excellent supplementary set for newer players looking to build a competitive deck on a budget.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What are the pull rates for Secret Rares in Destined Rivals?</summary>
        <p>On average, statistical distribution yields approximately two Secret Rares per 24-pack booster box. However, it is crucial to remember that these are average ratios across entire production runs; individual box contents can vary due to printing and collation variances.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Is the Destined Rivals card list legal for premier level tournament play?</summary>
        <p>Yes, all cards from the Destined Rivals set become completely legal for official sanctioned tournament play on the Friday of the set's official retail release week in your specific geographic region. Always check with your local head judge if you are unsure about a card's legality status.</p>
      </details>
